[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Theoretically, the stress ahead of a sharp crack tip becomes infinite and cannot be used to describe the state around a crack.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fracture mechanics is used to characterise the loads on a crack, typically using a single parameter to describe the complete loading state at the crack tip.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] A number of different parameters have been developed.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] When the **plastic zone** at the tip of the crack is small relative to the crack length the stress state at the crack tip is the result of elastic forces within the material and is termed **linear elastic fracture mechanics** (**LEFM**) and can be characterised using the stress intensity factor K .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Although the load on a crack can be arbitrary, in 1957 G.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] When the size of the plastic zone at the crack tip is too large, **elastic-plastic fracture mechanics** can be used with parameters such as the J-integral or the crack tip opening displacement.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The characterising parameter describes the state of the crack tip which can then be related to experimental conditions to ensure similitude.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Crack growth occurs when the parameters typically exceed certain critical values.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Corrosion may cause a crack to slowly grow when the stress corrosion stress intensity threshold is exceeded.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Similarly, small flaws may result in crack growth when subjected to cyclic loading.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Known as fatigue, it was found that for long cracks, the rate of growth is largely governed by the range of the stress intensity $\Delta K$ experienced by the crack due to the applied loading.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fast fracture will occur when the stress intensity exceeds the fracture toughness of the material.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The prediction of crack growth is at the heart of the damage tolerance mechanical design discipline.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The processes of material manufacture, processing, machining, and forming may introduce flaws in a finished mechanical component.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Arising from the manufacturing process, interior and surface flaws are found in all metal structures.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Not all such flaws are unstable under service conditions.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fracture mechanics is the analysis of flaws to discover those that are safe (that is, do not grow) and those that are liable to propagate as cracks and so cause failure of the flawed structure.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Despite these inherent flaws, it is possible to achieve through damage tolerance analysis the safe operation of a structure.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fracture mechanics as a subject for critical study has barely been around for a century and thus is relatively new.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] What crack size can be tolerated under service loading, i.e. what is the maximum permissible crack size?
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] How long does it take for a crack to grow from a certain initial size, for example the minimum detectable crack size, to the maximum permissible crack size?
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] What is the service life of a structure when a certain pre-existing flaw size (e.g. a manufacturing defect) is assumed to exist?
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] During the period available for crack detection how often should the structure be inspected for cracks?
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fracture mechanics was developed during World War I by English aeronautical engineer A.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Griffith – thus the term **Griffith crack** – to explain the failure of brittle materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] A theory was needed to reconcile these conflicting observations.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Also, experiments on glass fibers that Griffith himself conducted suggested that the fracture stress increases as the fiber diameter decreases.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Hence the uniaxial tensile strength, which had been used extensively to predict material failure before Griffith, could not be a specimen-independent material property.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Griffith suggested that the low fracture strength observed in experiments, as well as the size-dependence of strength, was due to the presence of microscopic flaws in the bulk material.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] To verify the flaw hypothesis, Griffith introduced an artificial flaw in his experimental glass specimens.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The artificial flaw was in the form of a surface crack which was much larger than other flaws in a specimen.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] An explanation of this relation in terms of linear elasticity theory is problematic.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Linear elasticity theory predicts that stress (and hence the strain) at the tip of a sharp flaw in a linear elastic material is infinite.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] To avoid that problem, Griffith developed a thermodynamic approach to explain the relation that he observed.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The growth of a crack, the extension of the surfaces on either side of the crack, requires an increase in the surface energy.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Griffith found an expression for the constant C in terms of the surface energy of the crack by solving the elasticity problem of a finite crack in an elastic plate.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where E is the Young's modulus of the material and $\gamma$ is the surface energy density of the material.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Assuming $E=62\ {\text{GPa}}$ and $\gamma =1\ {\text{J/m}}^{2}$ gives excellent agreement of Griffith's predicted fracture stress with experimental results for glass.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where $\sigma$ is the applied stress, a is half the crack length, and E is the Young's modulus, which for the case of plane strain should be divided by the plate stiffness factor $(1-\nu ^{2})$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The strain energy release rate can physically be understood as: *the rate at which energy is absorbed by growth of the crack*.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] If G ≥ $G_{c}$ , this is the criterion for which the crack will begin to propagate.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For materials highly deformed before crack propagation, the linear elastic fracture mechanics formulation is no longer applicable and an adapted model is necessary to describe the stress and displacement field close to crack tip, such as on fracture of soft materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Griffith's theory provides excellent agreement with experimental data for brittle materials such as glass.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For ductile materials such as steel, although the relation $\sigma _{f}{\sqrt {a}}=C$ still holds, the surface energy (*γ*) predicted by Griffith's theory is usually unrealistically high.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) during World War II realized that plasticity must play a significant role in the fracture of ductile materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In ductile materials (and even in materials that appear to be brittle), a plastic zone develops at the tip of the crack.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] As the applied load increases, the plastic zone increases in size until the crack grows and the elastically strained material behind the crack tip unloads.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The plastic loading and unloading cycle near the crack tip leads to the dissipation of energy as heat.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Hence, a dissipative term has to be added to the energy balance relation devised by Griffith for brittle materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In physical terms, additional energy is needed for crack growth in ductile materials as compared to brittle materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where $\gamma$ is the surface energy and $G_{p}$ is the plastic dissipation (and dissipation from other sources) per unit area of crack growth.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For brittle materials such as glass, the surface energy term dominates and $G\approx 2\gamma =2\,\,{\text{J/m}}^{2}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For ductile materials such as steel, the plastic dissipation term dominates and $G\approx G_{p}=1000\,\,{\text{J/m}}^{2}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For polymers close to the glass transition temperature, we have intermediate values of G between 2 and 1000 ${\text{J/m}}^{2}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Another significant achievement of Irwin and his colleagues was to find a method of calculating the amount of energy available for fracture in terms of the asymptotic stress and displacement fields around a crack front in a linear elastic solid.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where $\sigma _{ij}$ are the Cauchy stresses, r is the distance from the crack tip, $\theta$ is the angle with respect to the plane of the crack, and $f_{ij}$ are functions that depend on the crack geometry and loading conditions.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Irwin called the quantity K the stress intensity factor.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Since the quantity $f_{ij}$ is dimensionless, the stress intensity factor can be expressed in units of ${\text{MPa}}{\sqrt {\text{m}}}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Stress intensity replaced strain energy release rate and a term called fracture toughness replaced surface weakness energy.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where $K_{I}$ is the mode I stress intensity, $K_{c}$ the fracture toughness, and $\nu$ is Poisson's ratio.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Fracture occurs when $K_{I}\geq K_{c}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For the special case of plane strain deformation, $K_{c}$ becomes $K_{Ic}$ and is considered a material property.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The subscript I arises because of the different ways of loading a material to enable a crack to propagate.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The expression for $K_{I}$ will be different for geometries other than the center-cracked infinite plate, as discussed in the article on the stress intensity factor.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Consequently, it is necessary to introduce a dimensionless correction factor, Y , in order to characterize the geometry.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This correction factor, also often referred to as the *geometric shape factor*, is given by empirically determined series and accounts for the type and geometry of the crack or notch.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Irwin was the first to observe that if the size of the plastic zone around a crack is small compared to the size of the crack, the energy required to grow the crack will not be critically dependent on the state of stress (the plastic zone) at the crack tip.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In other words, a purely elastic solution may be used to calculate the amount of energy available for fracture.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where *U* is the elastic energy of the system and *a* is the crack length.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Either the load *P* or the displacement *u* are constant while evaluating the above expressions.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where *E* is the Young's modulus, *ν* is Poisson's ratio, and *K*I is the stress intensity factor in mode I.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Irwin also showed that the strain energy release rate of a planar crack in a linear elastic body can be expressed in terms of the mode I, mode II (sliding mode), and mode III (tearing mode) stress intensity factors for the most general loading conditions.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Next, Irwin adopted the additional assumption that the size and shape of the energy dissipation zone remains approximately constant during brittle fracture.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This assumption suggests that the energy needed to create a unit fracture surface is a constant that depends only on the material.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This new material property was given the name *fracture toughness* and designated *G*Ic.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Today, it is the critical stress intensity factor *K*Ic, found in the plane strain condition, which is accepted as the defining property in linear elastic fracture mechanics.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In theory the stress at the crack tip where the radius is nearly zero, would tend to infinity.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This would be considered a stress singularity, which is not possible in real-world applications.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For this reason, in numerical studies in the field of fracture mechanics, it is often appropriate to represent cracks as round tipped notches, with a geometry dependent region of stress concentration replacing the crack-tip singularity.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In actuality, the stress concentration at the tip of a crack within real materials has been found to have a finite value but larger than the nominal stress applied to the specimen.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Nevertheless, there must be some sort of mechanism or property of the material that prevents such a crack from propagating spontaneously.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The assumption is, the plastic deformation at the crack tip effectively blunts the crack tip.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This deformation depends primarily on the applied stress in the applicable direction (in most cases, this is the y-direction of a regular Cartesian coordinate system), the crack length, and the geometry of the specimen.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] To estimate how this plastic deformation zone extended from the crack tip, Irwin equated the yield strength of the material to the far-field stresses of the y-direction along the crack (x direction) and solved for the effective radius.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Models of ideal materials have shown that this zone of plasticity is centered at the crack tip.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This equation gives the approximate ideal radius of the plastic zone deformation beyond the crack tip, which is useful to many structural scientists because it gives a good estimate of how the material behaves when subjected to stress.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In the above equation, the parameters of the stress intensity factor and indicator of material toughness, $K_{C}$ , and the yield stress, $\sigma _{Y}$ , are of importance because they illustrate many things about the material and its properties, as well as about the plastic zone size.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For example, if $K_{c}$ is high, then it can be deduced that the material is tough, and if $\sigma _{Y}$ is low, one knows that the material is more ductile.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The ratio of these two parameters is important to the radius of the plastic zone.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] For instance, if $\sigma _{Y}$ is small, then the squared ratio of $K_{C}$ to $\sigma _{Y}$ is large, which results in a larger plastic radius.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This implies that the material can plastically deform, and, therefore, is tough.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This estimate of the size of the plastic zone beyond the crack tip can then be used to more accurately analyze how a material will behave in the presence of a crack.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The same process as described above for a single event loading also applies and to cyclic loading.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] If a crack is present in a specimen that undergoes cyclic loading, the specimen will plastically deform at the crack tip and delay the crack growth.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In the event of an overload or excursion, this model changes slightly to accommodate the sudden increase in stress from that which the material previously experienced.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] At a sufficiently high load (overload), the crack grows out of the plastic zone that contained it and leaves behind the pocket of the original plastic deformation.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Now, assuming that the overload stress is not sufficiently high as to completely fracture the specimen, the crack will undergo further plastic deformation around the new crack tip, enlarging the zone of residual plastic stresses.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This process further toughens and prolongs the life of the material because the new plastic zone is larger than what it would be under the usual stress conditions.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This allows the material to undergo more cycles of loading.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This idea can be illustrated further by the graph of Aluminum with a center crack undergoing overloading events.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] But a problem arose for the NRL researchers because naval materials, e.g., ship-plate steel, are not perfectly elastic but undergo significant plastic deformation at the tip of a crack.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] One basic assumption in Irwin's linear elastic fracture mechanics is small scale yielding, the condition that the size of the plastic zone is small compared to the crack length.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] However, this assumption is quite restrictive for certain types of failure in structural steels though such steels can be prone to brittle fracture, which has led to a number of catastrophic failures.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Linear-elastic fracture mechanics is of limited practical use for structural steels and Fracture toughness testing can be expensive.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Most engineering materials show some nonlinear elastic and inelastic behavior under operating conditions that involve large loads.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Historically, the first parameter for the determination of fracture toughness in the elasto-plastic region was the crack tip opening displacement (CTOD) or "opening at the apex of the crack" indicated.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This parameter was determined by Wells during the studies of structural steels, which due to the high toughness could not be characterized with the linear elastic fracture mechanics model.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] He noted that, before the fracture happened, the walls of the crack were leaving and that the crack tip, after fracture, ranged from acute to rounded off due to plastic deformation.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In addition, the rounding of the crack tip was more pronounced in steels with superior toughness.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] There are a number of alternative definitions of CTOD.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] In the two most common definitions, CTOD is the displacement at the original crack tip and the 90 degree intercept.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The latter definition was suggested by Rice and is commonly used to infer CTOD in finite element models of such.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Note that these two definitions are equivalent if the crack tip blunts in a semicircle.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Most laboratory measurements of CTOD have been made on edge-cracked specimens loaded in three-point bending.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Early experiments used a flat paddle-shaped gage that was inserted into the crack; as the crack opened, the paddle gage rotated, and an electronic signal was sent to an x-y plotter.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This method was inaccurate, however, because it was difficult to reach the crack tip with the paddle gage.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Today, the displacement V at the crack mouth is measured, and the CTOD is inferred by assuming the specimen halves are rigid and rotate about a hinge point (the crack tip).
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] An early attempt in the direction of elastic-plastic fracture mechanics was Irwin's **crack extension resistance curve**, Crack growth resistance curve or **R-curve**.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This curve acknowledges the fact that the resistance to fracture increases with growing crack size in elastic-plastic materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The R-curve is a plot of the total energy dissipation rate as a function of the crack size and can be used to examine the processes of slow stable crack growth and unstable fracture.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] However, the R-curve was not widely used in applications until the early 1970s.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The main reasons appear to be that the R-curve depends on the geometry of the specimen and the crack driving force may be difficult to calculate.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Cherepanov independently developed a new toughness measure to describe the case where there is sufficient crack-tip deformation that the part no longer obeys the linear-elastic approximation.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Rice's analysis, which assumes non-linear elastic (or monotonic deformation theory plastic) deformation ahead of the crack tip, is designated the J-integral.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This analysis is limited to situations where plastic deformation at the crack tip does not extend to the furthest edge of the loaded part.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] It also demands that the assumed non-linear elastic behavior of the material is a reasonable approximation in shape and magnitude to the real material's load response.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The elastic-plastic failure parameter is designated JIc and is conventionally converted to KIc using the equation below.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Also note that the J integral approach reduces to the Griffith theory for linear-elastic behavior.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] When a significant region around a crack tip has undergone plastic deformation, other approaches can be used to determine the possibility of further crack extension and the direction of crack growth and branching.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] A simple technique that is easily incorporated into numerical calculations is the *cohesive zone model* method which is based on concepts proposed independently by Barenblatt and Dugdale in the early 1960s.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The relationship between the Dugdale-Barenblatt models and Griffith's theory was first discussed by Willis in 1967.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The equivalence of the two approaches in the context of brittle fracture was shown by Rice in 1968.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Let a material have a yield strength $\sigma _{Y}$ and a fracture toughness in mode I $K_{Ic}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Based on fracture mechanics, the material will fail at stress $\sigma _{\text{fail}}=K_{Ic}/{\sqrt {\pi a}}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Based on plasticity, the material will yield when $\sigma _{fail}=\sigma _{Y}$ .
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] This value of a is called as **transition flaw size** $a_{t}$ ., and depends on the material properties of the structure.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] When the $a<a_{t}$ , the failure is governed by plastic yielding, and when $a>a_{t}$ the failure is governed by fracture mechanics.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] The value of $a_{t}$ for engineering alloys is 100 mm and for ceramics is 0.001 mm.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] If we assume that manufacturing processes can give rise to flaws in the order of micrometers, then, it can be seen that ceramics are more likely to fail by fracture, whereas engineering alloys would fail by plastic deformation.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Bažant (1983) proposed a crack band model for materials like concrete whose homogeneous nature changes randomly over a certain range.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] where $\sigma$ = stress intensity factor, $\tau$ = tensile strength, d = size of specimen, $\delta$ = maximum aggregate size, and $\lambda$ = an empirical constant.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] Atomistic Fracture Mechanics (AFM) is a relatively new field that studies the behavior and properties of materials at the atomic scale when subjected to fracture.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] It integrates concepts from fracture mechanics with atomistic simulations to understand how cracks initiate, propagate, and interact with the microstructure of materials.
[src:materials-science/fracture-mechanics] By using techniques like Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulations, AFM can provide insights into the fundamental mechanisms of crack formation and growth, the role of atomic bonds, and the influence of material defects and impurities on fracture behavior.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In materials science, a **grain boundary** is the interface between two grains, or crystallites, in a polycrystalline material.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Grain boundaries are two-dimensional defects in the crystal structure, and tend to decrease the electrical and thermal conductivity of the material.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Most grain boundaries are preferred sites for the onset of corrosion and for the precipitation of new phases from the solid.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] They are also important to many of the mechanisms of creep.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] On the other hand, grain boundaries disrupt the motion of dislocations through a material, so reducing crystallite size is a common way to improve mechanical strength, as described by the Hall–Petch relationship.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is convenient to categorize grain boundaries according to the extent of misorientation between the two grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] *Low-angle grain boundaries* (*LAGB*) or *subgrain boundaries* are those with a misorientation less than about 15 degrees.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Generally speaking they are composed of an array of dislocations and their properties and structure are a function of the misorientation.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In contrast the properties of *high-angle grain boundaries*, whose misorientation is greater than about 15 degrees (the transition angle varies from 10 to 15 degrees depending on the material), are normally found to be independent of the misorientation.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However, there are 'special boundaries' at particular orientations whose interfacial energies are markedly lower than those of general high-angle grain boundaries.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The simplest boundary is that of a tilt boundary where the rotation axis is parallel to the boundary plane.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] This boundary can be conceived as forming from a single, contiguous crystallite or grain which is gradually bent by some external force.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The energy associated with the elastic bending of the lattice can be reduced by inserting a dislocation, which is essentially a half-plane of atoms that act like a wedge, that creates a permanent misorientation between the two sides.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] As the grain is bent further, more and more dislocations must be introduced to accommodate the deformation resulting in a growing wall of dislocations – a low-angle boundary.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The grain can now be considered to have split into two sub-grains of related crystallography but notably different orientations.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] An alternative is a twist boundary where the misorientation occurs around an axis that is perpendicular to the boundary plane.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] This type of boundary incorporates two sets of screw dislocations.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] If the Burgers vectors of the dislocations are orthogonal, then the dislocations do not strongly interact and form a square network.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In other cases, the dislocations may interact to form a more complex hexagonal structure.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] These concepts of tilt and twist boundaries represent somewhat idealized cases.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The majority of boundaries are of a mixed type, containing dislocations of different types and Burgers vectors, in order to create the best fit between the neighboring grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] If the dislocations in the boundary remain isolated and distinct, the boundary can be considered to be low-angle.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] If deformation continues, the density of dislocations will increase and so reduce the spacing between neighboring dislocations.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Eventually, the cores of the dislocations will begin to overlap and the ordered nature of the boundary will begin to break down.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] At this point the boundary can be considered to be high-angle and the original grain to have separated into two entirely separate grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In comparison to low-angle grain boundaries, high-angle boundaries are considerably more disordered, with large areas of poor fit and a comparatively open structure.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Indeed, they were originally thought to be some form of amorphous or even liquid layer between the grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However, this model could not explain the observed strength of grain boundaries and, after the invention of electron microscopy, direct evidence of the grain structure meant the hypothesis had to be discarded.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is now accepted that a boundary consists of structural units which depend on both the misorientation of the two grains and the plane of the interface.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In this framework, it is possible to draw the lattice for the two grains and count the number of atoms that are shared (coincidence sites), and the total number of atoms on the boundary (total number of site).
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] For example, when Σ=3 there will be one atom of each three that will be shared between the two lattices.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Thus a boundary with high Σ might be expected to have a higher energy than one with low Σ.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Low-angle boundaries, where the distortion is entirely accommodated by dislocations, are Σ1.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Some other low-Σ boundaries have special properties, especially when the boundary plane is one that contains a high density of coincident sites.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Examples include coherent twin boundaries (e.g., Σ3) and high-mobility boundaries in FCC materials (e.g., Σ7).
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Deviations from the ideal CSL orientation may be accommodated by local atomic relaxation or the inclusion of dislocations at the boundary.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] A boundary can be described by the orientation of the boundary to the two grains and the 3-D rotation required to bring the grains into coincidence.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Thus a boundary has 5 macroscopic degrees of freedom.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However, it is common to describe a boundary only as the orientation relationship of the neighbouring grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Generally, the convenience of ignoring the boundary plane orientation, which is very difficult to determine, outweighs the reduced information.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The nature of the crystallography involved limits the misorientation of the boundary.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] A completely random polycrystal, with no texture, thus has a characteristic distribution of boundary misorientations (see figure).
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However, such cases are rare and most materials will deviate from this ideal to a greater or lesser degree.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The energy of a low-angle boundary is dependent on the degree of misorientation between the neighbouring grains up to the transition to high-angle status.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] with G is the shear modulus, $\nu$ is Poisson's ratio, and $r_{0}$ is the radius of the dislocation core.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It can be seen that as the energy of the boundary increases the energy per dislocation decreases.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Thus there is a driving force to produce fewer, more misoriented boundaries (i.e., grain growth).
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The situation in high-angle boundaries is more complex.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Although theory predicts that the energy will be a minimum for ideal CSL configurations, with deviations requiring dislocations and other energetic features, empirical measurements suggest the relationship is more complicated.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Some predicted troughs in energy are found as expected while others missing or substantially reduced.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The excess volume is another important property in the characterization of grain boundaries.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Excess volume was first proposed by Bishop in a private communication to Aaron and Bolling in 1972.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It describes how much expansion is induced by the presence of a GB and is thought that the degree and susceptibility of segregation is directly proportional to this.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Despite the name the excess volume is actually a change in length, this is because of the 2D nature of GBs the length of interest is the expansion normal to the GB plane.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] at constant temperature T , pressure p and number of atoms $n_{i}$ .
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Although a rough linear relationship between GB energy and excess volume exists the orientations where this relationship is violated can behave significantly differently affecting mechanical and electrical properties.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Experimental techniques have been developed which directly probe the excess volume and have been used to explore the properties of nanocrystalline copper and nickel.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Theoretical methods have also been developed and are in good agreement.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The movement of grain boundaries (HAGB) has implications for recrystallization and grain growth while subgrain boundary (LAGB) movement strongly influences recovery and the nucleation of recrystallization.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] A boundary moves due to a pressure acting on it.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is generally assumed that the velocity is directly proportional to the pressure with the constant of proportionality being the mobility of the boundary.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The apparent activation energy (Q) may be related to the thermally activated atomistic processes that occur during boundary movement.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However, there are several proposed mechanisms where the mobility will depend on the driving pressure and the assumed proportionality may break down.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is generally accepted that the mobility of low-angle boundaries is much lower than that of high-angle boundaries.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Since low-angle boundaries are composed of arrays of dislocations and their movement may be related to dislocation theory.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The most likely mechanism, given the experimental data, is that of dislocation climb, rate limited by the diffusion of solute in the bulk.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The movement of high-angle boundaries occurs by the transfer of atoms between the neighbouring grains.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] The ease with which this can occur will depend on the structure of the boundary, itself dependent on the crystallography of the grains involved, impurity atoms and the temperature.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is possible that some form of diffusionless mechanism (akin to diffusionless phase transformations such as martensite) may operate in certain conditions.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Some defects in the boundary, such as steps and ledges, may also offer alternative mechanisms for atomic transfer.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Since a high-angle boundary is imperfectly packed compared to the normal lattice it has some amount of *free space* or *free volume* where solute atoms may possess a lower energy.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] As a result, a boundary may be associated with a *solute atmosphere* that will retard its movement.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Only at higher velocities will the boundary be able to break free of its atmosphere and resume normal motion.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Both low- and high-angle boundaries are retarded by the presence of particles via the so-called Zener pinning effect.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] This effect is often exploited in commercial alloys to minimise or prevent recrystallization or grain growth during heat-treatment.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Grain boundaries are the preferential site for segregation of impurities, which may form a thin layer with a different composition from the bulk and a variety of atomic structures that are distinct from the abutting crystalline phases.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] For example, a thin layer of silica, which also contains impurity cations, is often present in silicon nitride.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Grain boundary complexions were introduced by Ming Tang, Rowland Cannon, and W.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] These grain boundary phases are thermodynamically stable and can be considered as quasi-two-dimensional phase, which may undergo to transition, similar to those of bulk phases.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In this case structure and chemistry abrupt changes are possible at a critical value of a thermodynamic parameter like temperature or pressure.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] This may strongly affect the macroscopic properties of the material, for example the electrical resistance or creep rates.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Grain boundaries can be analyzed using equilibrium thermodynamics but cannot be considered as phases, because they do not satisfy Gibbs' definition: they are inhomogeneous, may have a gradient of structure, composition or properties.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] For this reasons they are defined as complexion: an interfacial material or stata that is in thermodynamic equilibrium with its abutting phases, with a finite and stable thickness (that is typically 2–20 Å).
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] A complexion need the abutting phase to exist and its composition and structure need to be different from the abutting phase.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Contrary to bulk phases, complexions also depend on the abutting phase.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] For example, silica rich amorphous layer present in Si3N3, is about 10 Å thick, but for special boundaries this equilibrium thickness is zero.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Complexion can be grouped in 6 categories, according to their thickness: monolayer, bilayer, trilayer, nanolayer (with equilibrium thickness between 1 and 2 nm) and wetting.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In the first cases the thickness of the layer will be constant; if extra material is present it will segregate at multiple grain junction, while in the last case there is no equilibrium thickness and this is determined by the amount of secondary phase present in the material.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] One example of grain boundary complexion transition is the passage from dry boundary to biltilayer in Au-doped Si, which is produced by the increase of Au.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Grain boundaries can cause failure mechanically by embrittlement through solute segregation (see Hinkley Point A nuclear power station) but they also can detrimentally affect the electronic properties.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In metal oxides it has been shown theoretically that at the grain boundaries in Al2O3 and MgO the insulating properties can be significantly diminished.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Using density functional theory computer simulations of grain boundaries have shown that the band gap can be reduced by up to 45%.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In the case of metals grain boundaries increase the resistivity as the size of the grains relative to the mean free path of other scatters becomes significant.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It is known that most materials are polycrystalline and contain grain boundaries and that grain boundaries can act as sinks and transport pathways for point defects.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] However experimentally and theoretically determining what effect point defects have on a system is difficult.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Interesting examples of the complications of how point defects behave has been manifested in the temperature dependence of the Seebeck effect.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] In addition the dielectric and piezoelectric response can be altered by the distribution of point defects near grain boundaries.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Mechanical properties can also be significantly influenced with properties such as the bulk modulus and damping being influenced by changes to the distribution of point defects within a material.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] It has also been found that the Kondo effect within graphene can be tuned due to a complex relationship between grain boundaries and point defects.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Recent theoretical calculations have revealed that point defects can be extremely favourable near certain grain boundary types and significantly affect the electronic properties with a reduction in the band gap.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] Accurate modelling of grain boundaries both in terms of structure and atomic interactions could have the effect of improving engineering which could reduce waste and increase efficiency in terms of material usage and performance.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] From a computational point of view much of the research on grain boundaries has focused on bi-crystal systems, these are systems which only consider two grain boundaries.
[src:materials-science/grain-boundary] There has been recent work which has made use of novel grain evolution models which show that there are substantial differences in the material properties associated with whether curved or planar grains are present.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The intellectual origins of materials science stem from the Age of Enlightenment, when researchers began to use analytical thinking from chemistry, physics, and engineering to understand ancient, phenomenological observations in metallurgy and mineralogy.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science still incorporates elements of physics, chemistry, and engineering.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] As such, the field was long considered by academic institutions as a sub-field of these related fields.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Beginning in the 1940s, materials science began to be more widely recognized as a specific and distinct field of science and engineering, and major technical universities around the world created dedicated schools for its study.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] By studying how the history of a material (*processing*) influences its structure, properties, and performance, materials scientists have made many contributions to new technologies in biomaterials, metallurgy, and nanotechnology.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science is also used by forensic engineers and failure analysts to understand why and how critical components fail, which helps prevent dangerous and costly accidents in areas such as aviation.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The material of choice of a given era is often a defining point.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Phases such as Stone Age, Bronze Age, Iron Age, and Steel Age are historic, if arbitrary examples.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Originally deriving from the manufacture of ceramics and its putative derivative metallurgy, materials science is one of the oldest forms of engineering and applied science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Modern materials science evolved directly from metallurgy, which itself evolved from the use of fire.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A major breakthrough in the understanding of materials occurred in the late 19th century, when the American scientist Josiah Willard Gibbs demonstrated that the thermodynamic properties related to atomic structure in various phases are related to the physical properties of a material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Important elements of modern materials science were products of the Space Race; the understanding and engineering of the metallic alloys, and silica and carbon materials, used in building space vehicles enabling the exploration of space.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science has driven, and been driven by, the development of revolutionary technologies such as rubbers, plastics, semiconductors, and biomaterials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Before the 1960s (and in some cases decades after), many eventual *materials science* departments were *metallurgy* or *ceramics engineering* departments, reflecting the 19th and early 20th-century emphasis on metals and ceramics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Due to the expanded knowledge of the link between atomic and molecular processes as well as the overall properties of materials, the design of materials came to be based on specific desired properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The materials science field has since broadened to include every class of materials, including ceramics, polymers, semiconductors, magnetic materials, biomaterials, and nanomaterials, generally classified into three distinct groups: ceramics, metals, and polymers.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The prominent change in materials science during the recent decades is active usage of computer simulations to find new materials, predict properties and understand phenomena.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A material is defined as a substance (most often a solid, but other condensed phases can be included) that is intended to be used for certain applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] There are a myriad of materials around us; they can be found in anything from buildings and cars to spacecraft.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The main classes of materials are metals, semiconductors, ceramics and polymers.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] New and advanced materials that are being developed include nanomaterials, biomaterials, and energy materials to name a few.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The basis of materials science is studying the interplay between the structure of materials, the processing methods to make that material, and the resulting material properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The complex combination of these produce the performance of a material in a specific application.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Many features across many length scales impact material performance, from the constituent chemical elements, its microstructure, and macroscopic features from processing.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Together with the laws of thermodynamics and kinetics materials scientists aim to understand and improve materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Structure is one of the most important components of the field of materials science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The very definition of the field holds that it is concerned with the investigation of "the relationships that exist between the structures and properties of materials".
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science examines the structure of materials from the atomic scale, all the way up to the macro scale.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Characterization is the way materials scientists examine the structure of a material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This involves methods such as diffraction with X-rays, electrons or neutrons, and various forms of spectroscopy and chemical analysis such as Raman spectroscopy, energy-dispersive spectroscopy, chromatography, thermal analysis, electron microscope analysis, etc.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Structure is studied in the following levels.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Atomic structure deals with the atoms of the materials, and how they are arranged to give rise to molecules, crystals, etc.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Much of the electrical, magnetic and chemical properties of materials arise from this level of structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The length scales involved are in angstroms (Å).
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The chemical bonding and atomic arrangement (crystallography) are fundamental to studying the properties and behavior of any material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] To obtain a full understanding of the material structure and how it relates to its properties, the materials scientist must study how the different atoms, ions and molecules are arranged and bonded to each other.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This involves the study and use of quantum chemistry or quantum physics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Solid-state physics, solid-state chemistry and physical chemistry are also involved in the study of bonding and structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Crystallography is the science that examines the arrangement of atoms in crystalline solids.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Crystallography is a useful tool for materials scientists.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] One of the fundamental concepts regarding the crystal structure of a material includes the unit cell, which is the smallest unit of a crystal lattice (space lattice) that repeats to make up the macroscopic crystal structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Most common structural materials include parallelpiped and hexagonal lattice types.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] In single crystals, the effects of the crystalline arrangement of atoms is often easy to see macroscopically, because the natural shapes of crystals reflect the atomic structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Further, physical properties are often controlled by crystalline defects.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The understanding of crystal structures is an important prerequisite for understanding crystallographic defects.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Examples of crystal defects consist of dislocations including edges, screws, vacancies, self inter-stitials, and more that are linear, planar, and three dimensional types of defects.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] New and advanced materials that are being developed include nanomaterials, biomaterials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Mostly, materials do not occur as a single crystal, but in polycrystalline form, as an aggregate of small crystals or grains with different orientations.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Because of this, the powder diffraction method, which uses diffraction patterns of polycrystalline samples with a large number of crystals, plays an important role in structural determination.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Most materials have a crystalline structure, but some important materials do not exhibit regular crystal structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polymers display varying degrees of crystallinity, and many are completely non-crystalline.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Glass, some ceramics, and many natural materials are amorphous, not possessing any long-range order in their atomic arrangements.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The study of polymers combines elements of chemical and statistical thermodynamics to give thermodynamic and mechanical descriptions of physical properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials, which atoms and molecules form constituents in the nanoscale (i.e., they form nanostructures) are called nanomaterials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanomaterials are the subject of intense research in the materials science community due to the unique properties that they exhibit.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanostructure deals with objects and structures that are in the 1 – 100 nm range.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] In many materials, atoms or molecules agglomerate to form objects at the nanoscale.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This causes many interesting electrical, magnetic, optical, and mechanical properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] In describing nanostructures, it is necessary to differentiate between the number of dimensions on the nanoscale.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanotextured surfaces have *one dimension* on the nanoscale, i.e., only the thickness of the surface of an object is between 0.1 and 100 nm.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanotubes have *two dimensions* on the nanoscale, i.e., the diameter of the tube is between 0.1 and 100 nm; its length could be much greater.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Finally, spherical nanoparticles have *three dimensions* on the nanoscale, i.e., the particle is between 0.1 and 100 nm in each spatial dimension.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The terms nanoparticles and ultrafine particles (UFP) often are used synonymously although UFP can reach into the micrometre range.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The term 'nanostructure' is often used, when referring to magnetic technology.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanoscale structure in biology is often called ultrastructure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Microstructure is defined as the structure of a prepared surface or thin foil of material as revealed by a microscope above 25× magnification.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It deals with objects from 100 nm to a few cm.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The microstructure of a material (which can be broadly classified into metallic, polymeric, ceramic and composite) can strongly influence physical properties such as strength, toughness, ductility, hardness, corrosion resistance, high/low temperature behavior, wear resistance, and so on.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Most of the traditional materials (such as metals and ceramics) are microstructured.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The manufacture of a perfect crystal of a material is physically impossible.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] For example, any crystalline material will contain defects such as precipitates, grain boundaries (Hall–Petch relationship), vacancies, interstitial atoms or substitutional atoms.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The microstructure of materials reveals these larger defects and advances in simulation have allowed an increased understanding of how defects can be used to enhance material properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Macrostructure is the appearance of a material in the scale millimeters to meters, it is the structure of the material as seen with the naked eye.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials exhibit myriad properties, including the following.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The properties of a material determine its usability and hence its engineering application.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Synthesis and processing involves the creation of a material with the desired micro-nanostructure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A material cannot be used in industry if no economically viable production method for it has been developed.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Therefore, developing processing methods for materials that are reasonably effective and cost-efficient is vital to the field of materials science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Different materials require different processing or synthesis methods.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] For example, the processing of metals has historically defined eras such as the Bronze Age and Iron Age and is studied under the branch of materials science named *physical metallurgy*.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Chemical and physical methods are also used to synthesize other materials such as polymers, ceramics, semiconductors, and thin films.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] As of the early 21st century, new methods are being developed to synthesize nanomaterials such as graphene.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Thermodynamics is concerned with heat and temperature and their relation to energy and work.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It defines macroscopic variables, such as internal energy, entropy, and pressure, that partly describe a body of matter or radiation.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It states that the behavior of those variables is subject to general constraints common to all materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These general constraints are expressed in the four laws of thermodynamics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Thermodynamics describes the bulk behavior of the body, not the microscopic behaviors of the very large numbers of its microscopic constituents, such as molecules.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The behavior of these microscopic particles is described by, and the laws of thermodynamics are derived from, statistical mechanics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The study of thermodynamics is fundamental to materials science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It forms the foundation to treat general phenomena in materials science and engineering, including chemical reactions, magnetism, polarizability, and elasticity.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It explains fundamental tools such as phase diagrams and concepts such as phase equilibrium.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Chemical kinetics is the study of the rates at which systems that are out of equilibrium change under the influence of various forces.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] When applied to materials science, it deals with how a material changes with time (moves from non-equilibrium to equilibrium state) due to application of a certain field.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It details the rate of various processes evolving in materials including shape, size, composition and structure.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Diffusion is important in the study of kinetics as this is the most common mechanism by which materials undergo change.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Kinetics is essential in processing of materials because, among other things, it details how the microstructure changes with application of heat.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science is a highly active area of research.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Together with materials science departments, physics, chemistry, and many engineering departments are involved in materials research.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials research covers a broad range of topics; the following non-exhaustive list highlights a few important research areas.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanomaterials describe, in principle, materials of which a single unit is sized (in at least one dimension) between 1 and 1000 nanometers (10−9 meter), but is usually 1 nm – 100 nm.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nanomaterials research takes a materials science based approach to nanotechnology, using advances in materials metrology and synthesis, which have been developed in support of microfabrication research.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials with structure at the nanoscale often have unique optical, electronic, or mechanical properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The field of nanomaterials is loosely organized, like the traditional field of chemistry, into organic (carbon-based) nanomaterials, such as fullerenes, and inorganic nanomaterials based on other elements, such as silicon.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Examples of nanomaterials include fullerenes, carbon nanotubes, nanocrystals, etc.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A biomaterial is any matter, surface, or construct that interacts with biological systems.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering, and materials science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Biomaterials can be derived either from nature or synthesized in a laboratory using a variety of chemical approaches using metallic components, polymers, bioceramics, or composite materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] They are often intended or adapted for medical applications, such as biomedical devices which perform, augment, or replace a natural function.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Such functions may be benign, like being used for a heart valve, or may be bioactive with a more interactive functionality such as hydroxylapatite-coated hip implants.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Biomaterials are also used every day in dental applications, surgery, and drug delivery.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] For example, a construct with impregnated pharmaceutical products can be placed into the body, which permits the prolonged release of a drug over an extended period of time.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A biomaterial may also be an autograft, allograft or xenograft used as an organ transplant material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Semiconductors, metals, and ceramics are used today to form highly complex systems, such as integrated electronic circuits, optoelectronic devices, and magnetic and optical mass storage media.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Semiconductors are a traditional example of these types of materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] They are materials that have properties that are intermediate between conductors and insulators.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Their electrical conductivities are very sensitive to the concentration of impurities, which allows the use of doping to achieve desirable electronic properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Hence, semiconductors form the basis of the traditional computer.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This field also includes new areas of research such as superconducting materials, spintronics, metamaterials, etc.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The study of these materials involves knowledge of materials science and solid-state physics or condensed matter physics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] With continuing increases in computing power, simulating the behavior of materials has become possible.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This enables materials scientists to understand behavior and mechanisms, design new materials, and explain properties formerly poorly understood.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Efforts surrounding integrated computational materials engineering are now focusing on combining computational methods with experiments to drastically reduce the time and effort to optimize materials properties for a given application.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This involves simulating materials at all length scales, using methods such as density functional theory, molecular dynamics, Monte Carlo, dislocation dynamics, phase field, finite element, and many more.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Radical materials advances can drive the creation of new products or even new industries, but stable industries also employ materials scientists to make incremental improvements and troubleshoot issues with currently used materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Besides material characterization, the material scientist or engineer also deals with extracting materials and converting them into useful forms.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Thus ingot casting, foundry methods, blast furnace extraction, and electrolytic extraction are all part of the required knowledge of a materials engineer.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Often the presence, absence, or variation of minute quantities of secondary elements and compounds in a bulk material will greatly affect the final properties of the materials produced.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] For example, steels are classified based on 1/10 and 1/100 weight percentages of the carbon and other alloying elements they contain.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Thus, the extracting and purifying methods used to extract iron in a blast furnace can affect the quality of steel that is produced.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Solid materials are generally grouped into three basic classifications: ceramics, metals, and polymers.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This broad classification is based on the empirical makeup and atomic structure of the solid materials, and most solids fall into one of these broad categories.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] An item that is often made from each of these materials types is the beverage container.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The material types used for beverage containers accordingly provide different advantages and disadvantages, depending on the material used.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Ceramic (glass) containers are optically transparent, impervious to the passage of carbon dioxide, relatively inexpensive, and are easily recycled, but are also heavy and fracture easily.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Metal (aluminum alloy) is relatively strong, is a good barrier to the diffusion of carbon dioxide, and is easily recycled.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] However, the cans are opaque, expensive to produce, and are easily dented and punctured.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polymers (polyethylene plastic) are relatively strong, can be optically transparent, are inexpensive and lightweight, and can be recyclable, but are not as impervious to the passage of carbon dioxide as aluminum and glass.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Another application of materials science is the study of ceramics and glasses, typically the most brittle materials with industrial relevance.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Many ceramics and glasses exhibit covalent or ionic-covalent bonding with SiO2 (silica) as a fundamental building block.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Ceramics – not to be confused with raw, unfired clay – are usually seen in crystalline form.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The vast majority of commercial glasses contain a metal oxide fused with silica.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] At the high temperatures used to prepare glass, the material is a viscous liquid which solidifies into a disordered state upon cooling.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Windowpanes and eyeglasses are important examples.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Fibers of glass are also used for long-range telecommunication and optical transmission.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Scratch resistant Corning Gorilla Glass is a well-known example of the application of materials science to drastically improve the properties of common components.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Engineering ceramics are known for their stiffness and stability under high temperatures, compression and electrical stress.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Alumina, silicon carbide, and tungsten carbide are made from a fine powder of their constituents in a process of sintering with a binder.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Hot pressing provides higher density material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Chemical vapor deposition can place a film of a ceramic on another material.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Cermets are ceramic particles containing some metals.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The wear resistance of tools is derived from cemented carbides with the metal phase of cobalt and nickel typically added to modify properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Ceramics can be significantly strengthened for engineering applications using the principle of crack deflection.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This process involves the strategic addition of second-phase particles within a ceramic matrix, optimizing their shape, size, and distribution to direct and control crack propagation.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] This approach enhances fracture toughness, paving the way for the creation of advanced, high-performance ceramics in various industries.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Another application of materials science in industry is making composite materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These are structured materials composed of two or more macroscopic phases.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] One example is reinforced Carbon-Carbon (RCC), the light gray material, which withstands re-entry temperatures up to 1,510 °C (2,750 °F) and protects the Space Shuttle's wing leading edges and nose cap.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] RCC is a laminated composite material made from graphite rayon cloth and impregnated with a phenolic resin.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] After curing at high temperature in an autoclave, the laminate is pyrolized to convert the resin to carbon, impregnated with furfuryl alcohol in a vacuum chamber, and cured-pyrolized to convert the furfuryl alcohol to carbon.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] To provide oxidation resistance for reusability, the outer layers of the RCC are converted to silicon carbide.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Other examples can be seen in the "plastic" casings of television sets, cell-phones and so on.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These plastic casings are usually a composite material made up of a thermoplastic matrix such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS) in which calcium carbonate chalk, talc, glass fibers or carbon fibers have been added for added strength, bulk, or electrostatic dispersion.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These additions may be termed reinforcing fibers, or dispersants, depending on their purpose.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polymers are chemical compounds made up of a large number of identical components linked together like chains.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polymers are the raw materials (the resins) used to make what are commonly called plastics and rubber.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Plastics and rubber are the final product, created after one or more polymers or additives have been added to a resin during processing, which is then shaped into a final form.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Plastics in former and in current widespread use include polyethylene, polypropylene, polyvinyl chloride (PVC), polystyrene, nylons, polyesters, acrylics, polyurethanes, and polycarbonates.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Rubbers include natural rubber, styrene-butadiene rubber, chloroprene, and butadiene rubber.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Plastics are generally classified as *commodity*, *specialty* and *engineering* plastics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polyvinyl chloride (PVC) is widely used, inexpensive, and annual production quantities are large.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It lends itself to a vast array of applications, from artificial leather to electrical insulation and cabling, packaging, and containers.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Its fabrication and processing are simple and well-established.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The versatility of PVC is due to the wide range of plasticisers and other additives that it accepts.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The term "additives" in polymer science refers to the chemicals and compounds added to the polymer base to modify its material properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Polycarbonate would be normally considered an engineering plastic (other examples include PEEK, ABS).
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Such plastics are valued for their superior strengths and other special material properties.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] They are usually not used for disposable applications, unlike commodity plastics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Specialty plastics are materials with unique characteristics, such as ultra-high strength, electrical conductivity, electro-fluorescence, high thermal stability, etc.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The dividing lines between the various types of plastics is not based on material but rather on their properties and applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The alloys of iron (steel, stainless steel, cast iron, tool steel, alloy steels) make up the largest proportion of metals today both by quantity and commercial value.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Iron alloyed with various proportions of carbon gives low, mid and high carbon steels.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] An iron-carbon alloy is only considered steel if the carbon level is between 0.01% and 2.00% by weight.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] For steels, the hardness and tensile strength of the steel is related to the amount of carbon present, with increasing carbon levels also leading to lower ductility and toughness.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Heat treatment processes such as quenching and tempering can significantly change these properties, however.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] In contrast, certain metal alloys exhibit unique properties where their size and density remain unchanged across a range of temperatures.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Cast iron is defined as an iron–carbon alloy with more than 2.00%, but less than 6.67% carbon.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Stainless steel is defined as a regular steel alloy with greater than 10% by weight alloying content of chromium.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Nickel and molybdenum are typically also added in stainless steels.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Other significant metallic alloys are those of aluminium, titanium, copper and magnesium.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Copper alloys have been known for a long time (since the Bronze Age), while the alloys of the other three metals have been relatively recently developed.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Due to the chemical reactivity of these metals, the electrolytic extraction processes required were only developed relatively recently.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The alloys of aluminium, titanium and magnesium are also known and valued for their high strength to weight ratios and, in the case of magnesium, their ability to provide electromagnetic shielding.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These materials are ideal for situations where high strength to weight ratios are more important than bulk cost, such as in the aerospace industry and certain automotive engineering applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] A semiconductor is a material that has a resistivity between a conductor and insulator.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Modern day electronics run on semiconductors, and the industry had an estimated US$530 billion market in 2021.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Its electronic properties can be greatly altered through intentionally introducing impurities in a process referred to as doping.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Semiconductor materials are used to build diodes, transistors, light-emitting diodes (LEDs), and analog and digital electric circuits, among their many uses.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Semiconductor devices have replaced thermionic devices like vacuum tubes in most applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Semiconductor devices are manufactured both as single discrete devices and as integrated circuits (ICs), which consist of a number—from a few to millions—of devices manufactured and interconnected on a single semiconductor substrate.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Of all the semiconductors in use today, silicon makes up the largest portion both by quantity and commercial value.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Monocrystalline silicon is used to produce wafers used in the semiconductor and electronics industry.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Gallium arsenide (GaAs) is the second most popular semiconductor used.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Due to its higher electron mobility and saturation velocity compared to silicon, it is a material of choice for high-speed electronics applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] These superior properties are compelling reasons to use GaAs circuitry in mobile phones, satellite communications, microwave point-to-point links and higher frequency radar systems.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Other semiconductor materials include germanium, silicon carbide, and gallium nitride and have various applications.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials science evolved, starting from the 1950s because it was recognized that to create, discover and design new materials, one had to approach it in a unified manner.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The field of materials science and engineering is important both from a scientific perspective, as well as for applications field.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials are of the utmost importance for engineers (or other applied fields) because usage of the appropriate materials is crucial when designing systems.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] As a result, materials science is an increasingly important part of an engineer's education.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials physics is the use of physics to describe the physical properties of materials.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] It is a synthesis of physical sciences such as chemistry, solid mechanics, solid state physics, and materials science.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Materials physics is considered a subset of condensed matter physics and applies fundamental condensed matter concepts to complex multiphase media, including materials of technological interest.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Current fields that materials physicists work in include electronic, optical, and magnetic materials, novel materials and structures, quantum phenomena in materials, nonequilibrium physics, and soft condensed matter physics.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] New experimental and computational tools are constantly improving how materials systems are modeled and studied and are also fields when materials physicists work in.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The field is inherently interdisciplinary, and the materials scientists or engineers must be aware and make use of the methods of the physicist, chemist and engineer.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Conversely, fields such as life sciences and archaeology can inspire the development of new materials and processes, in bioinspired and paleoinspired approaches.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Thus, there remain close relationships with these fields.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] Conversely, many physicists, chemists and engineers find themselves working in materials science due to the significant overlaps between the fields.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] The main branches of materials science stem from the four main classes of materials: ceramics, metals, polymers and composites.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] There are additionally broadly applicable, materials independent, endeavors.
[src:materials-science/materials-science] There are also relatively broad focuses across materials on specific phenomena and techniques.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Although Young's modulus is named after the 19th-century British scientist Thomas Young, the concept was developed in 1727 by Leonhard Euler.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The first experiments that used the concept of Young's modulus in its modern form were performed by the Italian scientist Giordano Riccati in 1782, pre-dating Young's work by 25 years.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The term modulus is derived from the Latin root term *modus*, which means *measure*.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] A solid material undergoes elastic deformation when a small load is applied to it in compression or extension.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Elastic deformation is reversible, meaning that the material returns to its original shape after the load is removed.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] At near-zero stress and strain, the stress–strain curve is linear, and the relationship between stress and strain is described by Hooke's law that states stress is proportional to strain.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The coefficient of proportionality is Young's modulus.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The higher the modulus, the more stress is needed to create the same amount of strain; an idealized rigid body would have an infinite Young's modulus.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Conversely, a very soft material (such as a fluid) would deform without force, and would have zero Young's modulus.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus enables the calculation of the change in the dimension of a bar made of an isotropic elastic material under tensile or compressive loads.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] For instance, it predicts how much a material sample extends under tension or shortens under compression.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The Young's modulus directly applies to cases of uniaxial stress; that is, tensile or compressive stress in one direction and no stress in the other directions.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus is also used in order to predict the deflection that will occur in a statically determinate beam when a load is applied at a point in between the beam's supports.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Other elastic calculations usually require the use of one additional elastic property, such as the shear modulus G , bulk modulus K , and Poisson's ratio $\nu$ .
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Any two of these parameters are sufficient to fully describe elasticity in an isotropic material.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] For example, calculating physical properties of cancerous skin tissue, has been measured and found to be a Poisson's ratio of 0.43±0.12 and an average Young's modulus of 52 KPa.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Defining the elastic properties of skin may become the first step in turning elasticity into a clinical tool.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus represents the factor of proportionality in Hooke's law, which relates the stress and the strain.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] However, Hooke's law is only valid under the assumption of an *elastic* and *linear* response.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Any real material will eventually fail and break when stretched over a very large distance or with a very large force; however, all solid materials exhibit nearly Hookean behavior for small enough strains or stresses.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] If the range over which Hooke's law is valid is large enough compared to the typical stress that one expects to apply to the material, the material is said to be linear.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Otherwise (if the typical stress one would apply is outside the linear range), the material is said to be non-linear.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Steel, carbon fiber and glass among others are usually considered linear materials, while other materials such as rubber and soils are non-linear.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] However, this is not an absolute classification: if very small stresses or strains are applied to a non-linear material, the response will be linear, but if very high stress or strain is applied to a linear material, the linear theory will not be enough.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] For example, as the linear theory implies reversibility, it would be absurd to use the linear theory to describe the failure of a steel bridge under a high load; although steel is a linear material for most applications, it is not in such a case of catastrophic failure.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] In solid mechanics, the slope of the stress–strain curve at any point is called the tangent modulus.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] It can be experimentally determined from the slope of a stress–strain curve created during tensile tests conducted on a sample of the material.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus is not always the same in all orientations of a material.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Most metals and ceramics, along with many other materials, are isotropic, and their mechanical properties are the same in all orientations.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] However, metals and ceramics can be treated with certain impurities, and metals can be mechanically worked to make their grain structures directional.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] These materials then become anisotropic, and Young's modulus will change depending on the direction of the force vector.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Anisotropy can be seen in many composites as well.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] For example, carbon fiber has a much higher Young's modulus (is much stiffer) when force is loaded parallel to the fibers (along the grain).
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Other such materials include wood and reinforced concrete.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Engineers can use this directional phenomenon to their advantage in creating structures.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The Young's modulus of metals varies with the temperature and can be realized through the change in the interatomic bonding of the atoms, and hence its change is found to be dependent on the change in the work function of the metal.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Additionally, the Rahemi–Li model links the temperature dependence of Young’s modulus in metals to changes in the electron work function, providing a theoretical basis using a generalized Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus of a material can be used to calculate the force it exerts under specific strain.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] where F is the force exerted by the material when contracted or stretched by $\Delta L$ .
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Note that the elasticity of coiled springs comes from shear modulus, not Young's modulus.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] When a spring is stretched, its wire's length doesn't change, but its shape does.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] This is why only the shear modulus of elasticity is involved in the stretching of a spring.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] or, in simple notation, for a linear elastic material: ${\textstyle u_{e}(\varepsilon )=\int {E\,\varepsilon }\,d\varepsilon ={\frac {1}{2}}E{\varepsilon }^{2}}$ , since the strain is defined ${\textstyle \varepsilon \equiv {\frac {\Delta L}{L_{0}}}}$ .
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus can vary somewhat due to differences in sample composition and test method.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The rate of deformation has the greatest impact on the data collected, especially in polymers.
[src:materials-science/young-s-modulus] The values here are approximate and only meant for relative comparison.
